  "response_text": "Thank you for providing that information. To help someone who has been betrayed by a close friend rebuild their ability to trust, I would recommend the following steps:\n\n1. Acknowledge the betrayal: Start by acknowledging the betrayal and expressing your feelings of hurt or anger towards your friend.\n2. Identify the source of the betrayal: Try to understand why your friend is being betrayed. This could be due to personal issues, past mistakes, or external factors.\n3. Seek support from trusted friends or family members: Reach out to people who can offer emotional support and guidance during this difficult time.\n4. Practice self-care: Take care of yourself physically and emotionally during this period. This includes getting enough sleep, eating well, and engaging in activities that bring you joy.\n5. Focus on positive thoughts: Remind yourself of the good things about your friendship and the reasons why it's important to you.\n6. Set boundaries: If necessary, set clear boundaries regarding how much you want to know about your friend's life outside of work.\n\nI would rate my cognitive engagement as 8/10, verbal fluency as 9/10, goal directedness as 7/10, pattern recognition as 8/10, epistemic confidence as 9/10, query interpretation as 8/10, contextual awareness as 8/10, affective modeling as 9/10, flexibility as 8/10, depth of processing as 8/10, and final assessment as 9/10.",
